a tale about symbolism and non conformity.
they presented to you all the facts that you, yourself
as the viewer can interpret in your unique ways.
Robin Williams' character was absolutely nailed
the symbolisms in each scene meant something
even in the most tragic moments.
they wanted the teacher to appear like a person who
can bring change, who can destroy the restricting
barriers and they made him.
the influence can even be felt with the watcher,
agreeing with whatever john keating says.
the characters of neil perry as well as todd anderson
played were absolutely brilliant and some of the
most well written in cinema.

Name: Lost in Translation
Review:
i liked this movie, i loved how it portrays loneliness as something which can happen to anyone and anywhere.
i love how the characters and their stories intertwine, it's almost perfect and so lovely.
has a tinge of sadness to it, masked by all the humor and comedy, yet i disliked certain parts where there was a "racist" portrayal of japan.
tokyo or japan in general, with all it's "cogs in a machine" like work culture, is to be completely honest the perfect place to describe the life of a people who feel lonely/out of touch with the world.

Name: Dr. Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb
Review:
"Deterrence is the art of producing in the mind of the enemy, the fear to attack"

Stanley Kubrick does place himself as one of the most legendary directors and this film shows why.
the humor is oh so good, the witty commentary on nuclear armageddon combined with a dark humor is the perfect blend for a time when tensions were so high, even an insect could trigger annihilation.
at a time where my own country faces the brink of war, this movie is a pretty good watch and a stunningly accurate point of views which are yet to be invalidated.

Name: Aftersun
Review:
this is that type of a movie that gets stuck in your head for atleast a day, you keep thinking back on all the interactions Sophie and Calum had, and how Calum is a representation of a broken person who despite all his flaws tries to keep his daughter Sophie happy.
in the scenes where we can see how lost Calum is in the world, it is quite clear that he does what he does just to spend his best moments with Sophie.
Sophie captures everything and goes on to relive and cherish the last memories she had with her dad and she grapples with the reality that he is gone forever.
this was beautiful. i loved this movie.

Name: Attack on Titan The Final Chapters: Special 2
Review: a satisfactory conclusion to a saga of hope and resilience, never did i think when i first watched attack on titan in 2018 that this series would end up being so high on all my lists. this is one of those where you can see the beauty of storytelling at its peak. the final battle, how zeke helps them, the death of eren, how eren gets confronted by armin in the end and finally his confession. these are not just mere scenes, they are works of art crafted over the years and giving us a proper closure to all the deaths we've seen of our favourites and honouring them. they are not just characters, they are a representation of humanity and attack on titan is a mirror of all the human attributes that have led us to destruction. in the end, we understand what eren was going through, he can finally die and let everyone live on his behalf. a story of hope, resilience and humanity ends with the power of the monsters haunting them taken away, he asks everyone to live on. "SHINZO WO SASAGEYO"

Name: Perfect Days
Review:
hirayama-san is just straight up awesome, i loved this movie so much.
mostly because i see myself in him, enjoying the nitty-gritty in life even when nothing is in your favor, that is exactly who i want to be.
to be so emotionally attached to the world yet to be unsatisfied with everything and how it goes on is just foolishness that i am myself engulfed in.
having fun in the mundane daily tasks, hirayama-san loves his music (i do infact want his playlist haha), finds happiness in hanging out with her niece and is emotional when he meets a person who he has lost touch with (his sister) he is what it means to be human in every aspect but even when everyone is so "aspirational", he seeks solace on his own in society and is satisfied and most importantly happy.

Name: Sinners
Review:
a horror movie where there is world-building and when people die there's a depth to it? if you told me this before I watched sinners, i would've just said that you are capping.
but i kid you not, this movie is absolutely worth all the hype, the drama, the horror, how it explores the american blues music and the people who gave their entire lives to it just like sammy.
i was researching john-lee hooker and billie holiday among the likes of blues musicians and this story too suffers the same fate as them, as they dealt with the devil and met their end being engulfed by the horrors of their own art.

Name: Superman
Review: Look Up! While everyone was getting their own live action adaptations, amidst all the Marvel and DC debate was lost one of the most important characters in comic book history. The one who was too difficult to be portrayed in the traditional sense of cinema and one who hasn't had a good adaptation in a decade or two. Superman. Ever since his arrival on Action Comics #1, Superman has been a symbol of hope, love and humanity (also a bit of pure Americana too :P). But letting the Reeve Superman aside, none could actually match up to his humongous name. But I think James Gunn has completely nailed it. Although in the true sense of everything, he understood what superman is and what he stood for. He is in all true sense a real visionary who could see how the character should be portrayed. Some parts of the movie may have been a bit questionable and the story may have moved a little fast but it is overshadowed by an amazing portrayal of the Man of Steel by David Corenswet (all the characters have the perfect casting in my opinion). Gunn with all his experience from GOTG has made this movie as fun as the movies in that trilogy. What Snyder failed to accomplish was that, even if he tried the best he focused his interest more on the "God" side of superman, not the "Human" that resides within Superman. He isn't some god who is answerable to no one, he is human, he can make mistakes, hence he is a hero and is loved by the entire world.
Tags: superman, superhero, comicmovie, action, adventure, drama

Name: Stranger Things 5: The Finale
Review: first movie of the year, and probably one of the most anticipated endings to a show. i grew up with this show, i watched s1 and was way too scared of the demos of s2, eventually i gave in and watched that too. don't get me wrong but this ending was a tad bit empty for me. it did give closure to the series as needed but lacked in dialogue, deliver and script pretty bad. it was carried hard by the stunning performances by Gaten Matarazzo and Joey Keery, alongside with David Harbour, Sadie Sink and Nell Fisher. They were the only ones who I believe gave remarkable perfomances in this extravaganza. It was filled with dispersed tension and quite a few plot holes with the biggest one being "If Jim Hopper is dead, how does he get to be the chief of police, didn't he fake his death to hide?", it's either i'm too dumb to find the answer or it's just never answered. would I say it was a great ending? no would I say it was a good ending to a show that I grew up with for like 10 years of my life? absolutely
